'''''Galaxy''''' is a 1981 video game published by [[Avalon Hill]] and developed by [[Microcomputer Games]] for the [[Apple II]], [[TRS-80]], [[Atari 8-bit computers]], [[Commodore PET]], [[Commodore 64]], [[IBM PC compatible]]s, [[FM-7]], and [[TI-99/4A]]. It was originally published as '''''Galactic Empires''''' by Powersoft in 1979.<ref>{{Cite magazine|date=Jan–Feb 1982|title=Galaxy: Designer's Notes|volume=2|url=http://pdf.textfiles.com/zines/CGW/1982_0102_issue2.pdf|magazine=Computer Gaming World|issue=1}}</ref>

==Contents==
''Galaxy'' is a strategy game for up to 20 players, in which the object is to conquer the most planets within a number of turns as chosen by the players before the game starts.<ref name="SG"/>

==Reception==
[[Bruce Webster]] reviewed ''Galactic Empires'' in ''[[The Space Gamer]]'' No. 31.<ref name="SG2">{{cite journal|last=Webster|first=Bruce|author-link=Bruce Webster|date=September 1980|title=Featured Review: Galactic Empires|journal=[[The Space Gamer]]|publisher=[[Steve Jackson Games]]|issue=31|pages=14–15}}</ref> Webster commented that "It is one of the five best computer games and easily the best multi-player computer game I've ever seen."<ref name="SG2" />

Dana Holm reviewed ''Galaxy'' in ''[[The Space Gamer]]'' No. 61.<ref name="SG">{{cite journal|last=Holm |first=Dana |date=March 1983 |title=Capsule Reviews|journal=[[The Space Gamer]]|publisher=[[Steve Jackson Games]]|issue=61|pages=41}}</ref> Holm commented that "In the multi-player computer games market, there are not that many games.  This is a welcome addition to that collection."<ref name="SG" />

